From c1a0c3a3d8bb3a382100c6fd43293ac930bc54c6 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Max Furman <taygoth@gmail.com>
Date: Mon, 1 Jun 2026 00:20:07 +0500
Subject: [PATCH 6/9] media: i2c: imx363: start MCLK before supplies

Sony IMX-series datasheets require EXTCLK to be stable before reset
is deasserted. The current power-on sequence in imx363_power_on()
enables the bulk supplies and deasserts reset before enabling the
clock, which violates that requirement.

On most boards this happens to work because their pinctrl/clock
controllers bring MCLK up early. On the Xiaomi Mi 8 (sdm845, dipper)
with the Semco IMX363 module, however, mainline cam_cc_mclk0_clk
stays gated until the sensor driver calls clk_prepare_enable(), and
in that state the sensor never ACKs its own i2c address (read of
chip-id register returns -ENXIO from the CCI controller). EEPROM at
0x50 and actuator at 0x0e on the same bus respond normally, so this
is specifically the sensor failing to come up.

Reorder imx363_power_on() to start MCLK first, then ramp supplies,
then deassert reset, matching what the vendor sensor blob actually
encodes (MCLK -> VANA -> CUSTOM_GPIO1 -> VIO -> VDIG ->
RESET-deassert). Use fsleep() delays that stay safely within Sony's
"EXTCLK stable before reset deassertion" window. Also clean up on clk
error path.

The bulk-regulator ordering inside regulator_bulk_enable() is left
to the regulator core; only the relative ordering of MCLK vs
supplies vs reset is changed.

Sibling drivers built from the same template (imx258, imx355) likely
need the same fix; treated separately.

Signed-off-by: Max Furman <taygoth@gmail.com>
---
 drivers/media/i2c/imx363.c | 23 +++++++++++++++--------
 1 file changed, 15 insertions(+), 8 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/media/i2c/imx363.c b/drivers/media/i2c/imx363.c
index ff8d25dae..6b53d09a5 100644
--- a/drivers/media/i2c/imx363.c
+++ b/drivers/media/i2c/imx363.c
@@ -1039,25 +1039,32 @@ static int imx363_power_on(struct device *dev)
 	struct imx363 *imx363 = to_imx363(sd);
 	int ret;
 
+	/*
+	 * Sony EXTCLK must be stable before reset deassertion. Start
+	 * MCLK first, then bring up supplies, then deassert reset.
+	 */
+	ret = clk_prepare_enable(imx363->clk);
+	if (ret) {
+		dev_err(dev, "failed to enable clock\n");
+		return ret;
+	}
+
+	fsleep(1000);
+
 	ret = regulator_bulk_enable(IMX363_NUM_SUPPLIES,
 				    imx363->supplies);
 	if (ret) {
 		dev_err(dev, "%s: failed to enable regulators\n",
 			__func__);
+		clk_disable_unprepare(imx363->clk);
 		return ret;
 	}
 
-	usleep_range(400, 600);
+	fsleep(10000);
 
 	gpiod_set_value_cansleep(imx363->reset_gpio, 1);
 
-	ret = clk_prepare_enable(imx363->clk);
-	if (ret) {
-		dev_err(dev, "failed to enable clock\n");
-		regulator_bulk_disable(IMX363_NUM_SUPPLIES, imx363->supplies);
-	}
-
-	usleep_range(1000, 1200);
+	fsleep(20000);
 
 	return 0;
 }
